Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasPreElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: Relates a dissolution period to a pre-election dissolution period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PostElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: The period between the results of all constituency elections being announced and the next parliament period. During this period, successful candidates are Members even though Parliament is dissolved.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/parliamentNumber
Object: Parliament period has an ordinal number. Numbered from the Act of Union 1800. Parliaments are numbered ordinally from the first Parliament of the United Kingdom, sitting in 1801.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Recess
Object: A 'periodic adjournment' during a session, when one or both Houses have adjourned to a day other than the next expected sitting day. A periodic adjournment ends with prorogation, dissolution or a new term.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasRecess
Object: Relates a session to a recess.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasPrintingDay
Object: Relates a term to a printing day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PreElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: The period between the end of a parliament period and the results of all constituency elections being announced. During this time there are no Members of the House of Commons.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/ParliamentPeriod
Object: The time period of a Parliament between the date of its first assembly after a general election and the dissolution of that Parliament. We use the term Parliament period in this ontology to distinguish between a Parliament being a named period of time and Parliament as an institution. A Parliament period comprises contiguous periods while Parliament is either in session or prorogued. A Parliament period applies to both Houses. Proclamations naming dates for the assembly and dissolution of Parliaments are issued by the monarch. Before the passing of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, a dissolution proclamation named the date on which Parliament reassembled. After the passing of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, a Parliament begins on the date named in a proclamation issued following dissolution. The start date of a Parliament may be changed by subsequent proclamations. Before the passing of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, a dissolution proclamation named the date on which Parliament dissolved. After the passing of the Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011, the date of dissolution is determined according to that Act.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Session
Object: A period during which Parliament is able to conduct business on days of its choosing. A session is within a Parliament period. The first session of a Parliament begins on the same day as the Parliament period and ends on a day named in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the Parliament period begin and end on dates named in subsequent prorogation proclamations. The final session of a Parliament ends either with prorogation followed by dissolution or with dissolution. Session periods are the same for both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasRecessPrintingDay
Object: Relates a recess to a printing day. Allows for printing days to happen in a recess period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PrintingDay
Object: In the House of Commons, a printing day is a non-sitting day during an adjournment (not including a non-sitting Friday) on which any parliamentary questions or amendments to Bills tabled since the last sitting day are published. The parliamentary questions so published are not officially tabled until the next sitting day, but under House of Commons Standing Order No. 64 (retrieved at 17/04/2018), amendments to Bills received before 16h30 on the last business day of the period are treated as if that day were a sitting day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/proposedEndDate
Object: Time period has a proposed end date.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/House
Object: A parliamentary House e.g. the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasTerm
Object: Relates a session to a term.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/TimePeriod
Object: A period of time, having a name. An interval rather than a single point in time.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasPostElectionDissolutionPeriod
Object: Relates a dissolution period to a post-election dissolution period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasTablingDay
Object: Relates a term to a tabling day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/houseHasRecess
Object: Relates a House to a recess. Allows for different recess periods in different Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Term
Object: A period between recess periods during which a House may be sitting. Term periods are not necessarily the same across both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/TablingDay
Object: A day on which a Member of a House may table a question. In the House of Commons questions are tabled on sitting days. In the House of Lords questions are tabled on sitting days and  on selected recess days.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasRecessTablingDay
Object: Relates a recess to a tabling day. Allows for tabling days to happen in a recess period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasSittingDay
Object: Relates a term to a sitting day.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/Reign
Object: A period of time during which a monarch has a reign in a kingdom.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/DissolutionPeriod
Object: The period during which Parliament is dissolved. During this time no parliamentary business can take place. From the time of dissolution until the returning of a result for a constituency in a general election, that constituency has no Member sitting in the House of Commons. Winners returned for a constituency in a general election are Members from the time of being returned, even if Parliament is dissolved. Members of the House of Lords retain their memberships during a dissolution period. A dissolution period applies to both Houses. A proclamation to dissolve Parliament is made under a prerogative power of the Crown.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasSession
Object: Relates a Parliament period to a session.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/hasProrogationPeriod
Object: Relates a Parliament period to a prorogation period.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/proposedStartDate
Object: Time period has a proposed start date.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/ProrogationPeriod
Object: The time period between a prorogation and either dissolution or the start of the subsequent session. A prorogation period is within a Parliament period. Parliamentary business does not take place during a prorogation period. A prorogation period is the same across both Houses. A proclamation to prorogue Parliament is made under a prerogative power of the Crown.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/houseHasTerm
Object: Relates a House to a term. Allows for different term periods in different Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/PremiershipPeriod
Object: A continuous period of government under a single Prime Minister, spanning general elections, for example: Thatcher administration 1979-1990.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/SittingDay
Object: A day on which a House is sitting. Sitting days are not the same across both Houses. A sitting day may continue after midnight and therefore cross more than one calendar day, but it is known by the day on which it started.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-point/
Object: A model describing time periods used by the UK Parliament.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/time-period/GovernmentAdministrationPeriod
Object: A period of a single government, under a single Prime Minister, bounded by general elections, for example: Thatcher administration 1979-1983, Thatcher administration 1983-1987, Thatcher administration 1987-1990.
